Summary of Ferns and Petals:

The sales dashboard provides ease of view of business performance across 1,000 total orders with a total revenue of £3,520,984. Customer engagement and operational efficiency appear strong, reflected in an average customer spend of £3,520.98 and an average delivery time of 5.53 days. 
________________________________________
1. Revenue Performance
Revenue by Occasion
Sales are strongly event-driven. The highest-performing occasions are:
•	Anniversary – the largest revenue generator at £674k
•	All Occasions – £585k
•	Raksha Bandhan and Holi – both around £631k and £574k respectively
•	Lower revenue is observed during Birthday, Diwali, and Valentine’s Day, each between £313k–£418k.  However, the revenue peaks in February despite the lower revenue of Valentine’s, likely due to preparation for Holi. 
Insight: Marketing and product bundling for high-revenue occasions should be reinforced, while lower-revenue occasions might benefit from targeted promotions. Consideration to be made for why the month with Valentine’s is peak revenue despite the occasion itself having low revenue
________________________________________
2. Revenue by Category 
The strongest product categories include:
•	Colors – leading with approx. £1M in revenue
•	Sweets and Soft Toys – approx. £730k–£740k each
•	Cake, Plants, and Mugs – significantly lower, between £200k–£330k
Insight: Colors, Sweets, and Soft Toys show the highest demand and should remain central to the product strategy. Underperforming categories may need repositioning or product refresh.
________________________________________
3. Revenue by Hour (Order Time) 
Sales are relatively consistent throughout the day, with notable peaks at:
•	Sales throughout the day, starting at midnight, show an increasing trend in revenue. Begins at a low peak of £99k and gradually increases, with the exception of a drop at 10am to 94k in revenue before climbing once again
Insight: Peak hours can be leveraged for timed promotions, staffing optimization, and dynamic pricing.
________________________________________
4. Monthly Revenue Trends 
Revenue shows high seasonality:
•	8 months of the year have relatively low revenues (ranging £97k to £157k) with 4 significant spikes around occasions. 
•	Peak in February and March – relating to Valentines Day and Holi (gifts and products purchased in February in preparation for Holi contribute to the significant spike of revenue. Colours are the predominate category for revenue over both months and represents an opportunity for promotion in January in preparation for both of these occasions (January is the lowest revenue month at £97k and may benefit from this)
•	August, and November (£737k and £449k respectively). Peaks for Raksha Bandhan and Diwali. 
o	Toys, Colours and Sweets make up a majority of the revenue for Raksha Bandhan 
o	Sweets make up a majority of the revenue for Diwali, Colours, soft toys and plants are 3 of the next highest revenues and combined they make approximately the same as sweets
Insight: Strong seasonal swings indicate opportunities for promotional intensification during off-peak months. E.g., gift sets containing sweets in September/October in preparation for Diwali 
________________________________________
5. Top 5 Products by Revenue 
Leading products include:
•	Magham Set – approx. £120k
•	Dolores Gift, Harum Pack, and Quia Gift – approx. £100k–£115k
•	Deserunt Box – approx. £97k
Insight: These high-performing items could be bundled for festive seasons or used in targeted marketing campaigns. While these are the top products throughout the year, the top products change and have significant spikes around each of the occasions. 
Overall Business Health
The business shows strong revenue concentration around certain occasions and product categories. Seasonal patterns and hourly demand fluctuations present clear operational and marketing opportunities. Geographic order distribution suggests targeted growth markets.
